{
  "Which state of matter has a definite shape and a definite volume?": "",
  "Plasma": "",
  "Liquid": "",
  "Solid": "",
  "Gas": "",
  "Solids have particles tightly packed in fixed positions, giving them both a definite shape and a definite volume. Liquids have definite volume but not shape; gases have neither.": "",
  "Which state of matter has no definite shape and no definite volume?": "",
  "Crystal": "",
  "Gas particles are far apart and move freely, so a gas will expand to fill whatever container it occupies — it has neither a definite shape nor a definite volume.": "",
  "In which state of matter can particles slide past one another while staying close together?": "",
  "Liquid particles are close together (giving liquids a definite volume) but can move past each other, which is why liquids flow and take the shape of their container.": "",
  "What is the fourth state of matter, commonly found in stars and lightning?": "",
  "Vapor": "",
  "Condensate": "",
  "Gel": "",
  "Plasma is an ionized gas made of free-moving electrons and ions. It is created at extremely high temperatures and is the most abundant state of matter in the universe (stars, lightning, neon signs).": "",
  "What happens to particle motion when the temperature of a substance increases?": "",
  "Particles slow down": "",
  "Particle motion stays the same": "",
  "Particles stop moving": "",
  "Particles move faster": "",
  "Temperature is a measure of average kinetic energy. When temperature increases, particles gain energy and move faster and more vigorously.": "",
  "Which state of matter has particles that vibrate in place but do not move freely?": "",
  "In a solid, particles are locked in fixed positions and can only vibrate. They do not move freely like liquid or gas particles. This is why solids maintain a definite shape.": "",
  "Which state of matter has the highest average kinetic energy at a given temperature?": "",
  "They are all equal": "",
  "Gas particles move the fastest and most freely, giving them the highest kinetic energy among the three common states. Solids have the lowest kinetic energy because their particles only vibrate in place.": "",
  "A gas will expand to fill its container because its particles are:": "",
  "Completely stationary": "",
  "Far apart and moving at high speeds": "",
  "Tightly packed and vibrating": "",
  "Close together and sliding past each other": "",
  "Gas particles are widely spaced and move rapidly in all directions. Because of this, they spread out to occupy the entire volume of any container they are placed in.": "",
  "Which state of matter is the most common in the visible universe?": "",
  "Plasma makes up over 99% of the visible universe. Stars, including our Sun, are made of plasma. On Earth, plasma is less common but appears in lightning, neon signs, and fluorescent lights.": "",
  "Liquids have a definite _____ but not a definite _____.": "",
  "Shape; volume": "",
  "Volume; shape": "",
  "Mass; color": "",
  "Temperature; density": "",
  "Liquid particles are close enough together to maintain a fixed volume, but they can slide past each other, so a liquid takes the shape of whatever container it is in.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'solid' in chemistry?": "",
  "A substance that always dissolves in water": "",
  "Matter with a definite shape and definite volume whose particles vibrate in fixed positions": "",
  "Any material that is hard to the touch": "",
  "Matter that flows freely and has no definite shape": "",
  "A solid is a state of matter where particles are tightly packed in fixed, ordered positions. They vibrate but do not translate freely, giving solids both a definite shape and a definite volume.": "",
  "What does 'kinetic energy' mean in the context of states of matter?": "",
  "The total mass of all particles in a sample": "",
  "The energy required to break a molecule apart": "",
  "The energy stored in chemical bonds": "",
  "The energy of particle motion — faster particles have more kinetic energy": "",
  "Kinetic energy (KE = ½mv²) is the energy a particle possesses due to its motion. In the context of states of matter, higher kinetic energy means particles move faster, which is directly related to higher temperature.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'plasma'?": "",
  "A liquid with extremely low viscosity": "",
  "An ionized gas of free electrons and ions formed at very high temperatures": "",
  "A very cold gas found in deep space": "",
  "A solid that conducts electricity": "",
  "Plasma is the fourth state of matter, formed when a gas is heated to such high temperatures that atoms become ionized — electrons are stripped away, creating a mix of free electrons and positive ions.": "",
  "What does the term 'phase' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "The speed at which particles move": "",
  "A physically distinct form of matter — solid, liquid, gas, or plasma": "",
  "A step in a chemical reaction": "",
  "The color of a substance": "",
  "A phase is a distinct form of matter with uniform physical properties. The most common phases are solid, liquid, gas, and plasma. Phase changes occur when energy is added or removed.": "",
  "What is 'viscosity'?": "",
  "The temperature at which a liquid boils": "",
  "A liquid's resistance to flow, caused by intermolecular forces between particles": "",
  "The density of a solid material": "",
  "The amount of gas dissolved in a liquid": "",
  "Viscosity measures how much a fluid resists flowing. Honey has high viscosity (flows slowly) while water has low viscosity (flows easily). Stronger intermolecular forces lead to higher viscosity.": "",
  "What are 'intermolecular forces'?": "",
  "Forces inside the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "Attractive forces between molecules that influence a substance's physical properties and state": "",
  "The bonds between atoms within a single molecule": "",
  "Gravitational pull between large objects": "",
  "Intermolecular forces (IMFs) are attractions between neighboring molecules. They determine melting point, boiling point, viscosity, and which state of matter a substance exists in at a given temperature. Stronger IMFs mean higher melting/boiling points.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'thermal energy'?": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all particles in a substance": "",
  "The energy needed to change an object's shape": "",
  "The energy released during a nuclear reaction": "",
  "The potential energy stored in chemical bonds": "",
  "Thermal energy is the sum of the kinetic energies of all particles in a substance. It increases with temperature and with the amount of matter in the sample.": "",
  "What does 'surface tension' mean?": "",
  "The hardness of a solid surface": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a gas on container walls": "",
  "The rate at which a liquid evaporates": "",
  "The tendency of a liquid's surface to resist being stretched or broken, due to intermolecular forces": "",
  "Surface tension is caused by the net inward pull of intermolecular forces on molecules at a liquid's surface. This creates a 'skin-like' barrier that allows small objects (like water striders) to rest on the surface.": "",
  "What is 'absolute zero'?": "",
  "The temperature at which water freezes (0°C)": "",
  "The temperature at which all matter becomes plasma": "",
  "The average temperature in outer space": "",
  "The lowest possible temperature (0 K or −273.15°C) where particle motion theoretically stops": "",
  "Absolute zero (0 Kelvin, −273.15°C) is the theoretical lower limit of temperature. At this point, particles would have minimum possible energy and essentially no thermal motion. It has never been fully reached in practice.": "",
  "What does 'amorphous solid' mean?": "",
  "A solid that is always transparent": "",
  "A solid that easily dissolves in water": "",
  "A solid with a very high melting point": "",
  "A solid that lacks an ordered, repeating crystalline structure": "",
  "Amorphous solids (like glass, rubber, and some plastics) lack the long-range ordered arrangement of particles found in crystalline solids. They soften gradually over a range of temperatures rather than melting at a sharp melting point.": "",
  "A student leaves an ice cube on the kitchen counter. After 20 minutes, there is a puddle of water. Which states of matter are demonstrated in this observation?": "",
  "Solid changing to liquid — the ice melted as it absorbed thermal energy from the room": "",
  "Plasma changing to solid — the ice was formed from plasma": "",
  "Gas changing to liquid — water vapor condensed on the counter": "",
  "Liquid changing to gas — the water evaporated quickly": "",
  "The ice cube (solid) absorbed heat energy from the warmer room. Once enough energy was gained to overcome the intermolecular forces holding the solid structure, the particles began moving more freely, producing liquid water.": "",
  "A helium balloon rises into the sky and eventually pops. As it rose, the balloon got larger. Which property of gases explains why the balloon expanded?": "",
  "The rubber of the balloon melted in the sunlight": "",
  "The helium changed from gas to plasma at high altitude": "",
  "Gas particles spread out to fill available space — lower atmospheric pressure at altitude allows expansion": "",
  "Gravity compressed the gas, making the balloon wider": "",
  "Gases have no definite volume and will expand to equalize pressure. As the balloon rose, atmospheric pressure decreased, so the helium inside pushed outward more strongly than the outside air pushed in, causing the balloon to expand until it popped.": "",
  "A welder's arc produces temperatures above 10,000°C and a bright glowing stream. What state of matter is most likely present at the tip of the welding arc?": "",
  "Liquid — the metal melts and glows red": "",
  "Plasma — the extreme temperature ionizes atoms into free electrons and ions": "",
  "Solid — the metal stays solid but emits light": "",
  "Gas — the metal simply evaporates at high temperature": "",
  "At temperatures above 10,000°C, atoms gain enough energy to ionize — electrons are stripped from their atoms, creating plasma. The bright glow comes from ions and electrons recombining and emitting photons of light.": "",
  "A sealed syringe filled with air is compressed by pushing the plunger in. The volume decreases but no air escapes. Which property of gases allows this compression?": "",
  "The air converts to a liquid under pressure": "",
  "Gas particles are tightly packed and slide past each other": "",
  "Gas particles are far apart with empty space between them, allowing them to be pushed closer together": "",
  "The syringe walls absorb the gas molecules": "",
  "Unlike solids and liquids, gas particles have large amounts of empty space between them. When pressure is applied, the particles can be forced closer together, reducing the volume. This is why gases are compressible while liquids and solids are essentially incompressible.": "",
  "Dry ice (solid CO₂) is placed on a table and produces white fog while shrinking, but no puddle forms underneath. What process is occurring?": "",
  "Deposition — the gas is forming ice crystals": "",
  "Evaporation — the liquid CO₂ is turning into gas too fast to see": "",
  "Sublimation — the solid CO₂ is converting directly to gas without becoming a liquid": "",
  "Condensation — the CO₂ gas is turning back into a solid": "",
  "At normal atmospheric pressure, CO₂ goes directly from solid to gas (sublimation) without passing through the liquid phase. The white 'fog' is actually water vapor from the surrounding air condensing due to the extreme cold of the dry ice.": "",
  "A chef notices that honey flows much more slowly than water when poured from a spoon. Both are liquids, so what property explains why honey flows more slowly?": "",
  "Density — honey is denser so gravity pulls it down faster": "",
  "Viscosity — honey has stronger intermolecular forces, making it more resistant to flow": "",
  "Temperature — honey is always colder than water": "",
  "Surface tension — honey has a stronger surface skin": "",
  "Viscosity is a liquid's resistance to flow. Honey has strong intermolecular forces between its sugar molecules, making it highly viscous. Water has weaker intermolecular forces and therefore lower viscosity. Warming honey reduces its viscosity.": "",
  "A camper notices that water boils at about 95°C at their mountain campsite instead of the usual 100°C at sea level. What causes this difference?": "",
  "Cold mountain air cools the water faster so it boils sooner": "",
  "Mountain water contains different minerals that lower the boiling point": "",
  "Lower atmospheric pressure at high altitude means less energy is needed for particles to escape as gas": "",
  "The campfire produces less heat at high altitude": "",
  "Boiling occurs when a liquid's vapor pressure equals the atmospheric pressure above it. At higher altitude, atmospheric pressure is lower, so less energy (lower temperature) is needed for water molecules to escape into the gas phase.": "",
  "A scientist places an iron block, a wooden block, and a sealed balloon in a box. She compresses only the balloon significantly. Why can the gas be compressed but the solid objects cannot?": "",
  "Gas particles are smaller than solid particles": "",
  "The balloon is made of rubber, which is more flexible than iron or wood": "",
  "Solids are heavier than gases so they resist compression": "",
  "Gas particles have large spaces between them that can be reduced; solid particles are already packed closely together": "",
  "Compressibility depends on the spacing between particles, not their size or weight. Gas particles are widely spaced with mostly empty space, so they can be pushed closer together. Solid (and liquid) particles are already close, leaving almost no room for compression.": "",
  "Neon signs glow with bright colors when electricity passes through the gas inside the tube. What state of matter produces the characteristic glow?": "",
  "Solid — solid neon crystals emit light when struck by electricity": "",
  "Plasma — electricity ionizes the neon gas, and ions emit light when electrons return to lower energy levels": "",
  "Liquid — melted neon produces light when heated": "",
  "Gas — neon gas naturally glows at room temperature": "",
  "When high-voltage electricity passes through a sealed tube of neon gas, it ionizes the atoms — stripping electrons and creating plasma. As the excited electrons fall back to lower energy levels, they emit photons of visible light, producing the characteristic neon glow.": "",
  "A forensic scientist discovers an unknown clear liquid at a crime scene. She measures its boiling point as 78.37°C and its density as 0.789 g/mL, which match known values for ethanol. Why can these two measurements identify the substance?": "",
  "Boiling point and density are intensive properties — they are characteristic of a substance regardless of sample size": "",
  "Every liquid has a unique color that corresponds to its boiling point": "",
  "The amount of liquid determines its boiling point": "",
  "Mass and volume always identify a substance": "",
  "Boiling point and density are intensive properties — they do not change with the amount of substance. Each pure substance has unique intensive property values that act like a fingerprint. Mass and volume alone (extensive properties) change with sample size and cannot identify a substance.": ""
}